00:57:30.600 --> 00:57:32.710
You share a story.

00:57:32.710 --> 00:57:34.007
It kind of captivates you.

00:57:34.007 --> 00:57:35.590
There's a confusing
thing that's going

00:57:35.590 --> 00:57:37.862
on-- a confusing phenomenon.

00:57:37.862 --> 00:57:39.445
Doctors will kind
of give they're take

00:57:39.445 --> 00:57:42.186
and sometimes will give
us a bit of a resolution.

00:57:42.186 --> 00:57:44.060
And early in the book,
one of the resolutions

00:57:44.060 --> 00:57:49.820
is the self is linked to one's
body, one's story, and one's

00:57:49.820 --> 00:57:52.520
social and cultural milieu.

00:57:52.520 --> 00:57:55.670
Brain, body, mind,
self, and society

00:57:55.670 --> 00:57:57.760
are inextricably linked.

00:57:57.760 --> 00:57:59.890
What I liked about
this-- what provoked

00:57:59.890 --> 00:58:02.770
some thought in me
is I think we take

00:58:02.770 --> 00:58:05.280
a lot of these aspects
of our self for granted.

00:58:05.280 --> 00:58:06.580
We know we have a body.

00:58:06.580 --> 00:58:07.250
We have a mind.

00:58:07.250 --> 00:58:10.390
We have feelings--
a sense of self.

00:58:10.390 --> 00:58:13.150
But this idea of bringing
society into the equation

00:58:13.150 --> 00:58:16.430
is interesting because
I find we blame society

00:58:16.430 --> 00:58:18.800
a lot for a lot for things
that we don't like instead

00:58:18.800 --> 00:58:20.680
of thinking it may
be, or even realizing

00:58:20.680 --> 00:58:21.850
that it's part of ourselves.

00:58:21.850 --> 00:58:24.070
So at Google, we take on
a lot of social issues.

00:58:24.070 --> 00:58:25.370
We think about them.

00:58:25.370 --> 00:58:27.724
We say at Google
society has standards

00:58:27.724 --> 00:58:29.890
that women shouldn't be
engineers or women shouldn't

00:58:29.890 --> 00:58:32.490
be CEOs or directors or VPs.

00:58:32.490 --> 00:58:35.160
And we combat
society in that way.

00:58:35.160 --> 00:58:37.220
What I wonder-- my very
long-winded question

00:58:37.220 --> 00:58:40.540
is-- if we can acknowledge
that the society--

00:58:40.540 --> 00:58:43.460
culture is at some point,
just a part of ourselves.

00:58:43.460 --> 00:58:46.340
Does it not liberate
us to then maybe think

00:58:46.340 --> 00:58:48.030
about how much we
want to give a voice

00:58:48.030 --> 00:58:49.113
to that part of ourselves?

00:58:50.810 --> 00:58:53.060
ANIL ANANTHASWAMY: Yeah, I
think it's really important

00:58:53.060 --> 00:58:55.160
to acknowledge the role
of culture and society

00:58:55.160 --> 00:58:55.830
in who we are.

00:58:55.830 --> 00:59:00.170
We were talking about this
before the talk began.

00:59:00.170 --> 00:59:05.925
And I was telling Sajit
that he's off Indian origin?

00:59:05.925 --> 00:59:07.627
MALE SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:59:07.627 --> 00:59:09.460
ANIL ANANTHASWAMY: But
he grew up in the US.

00:59:09.460 --> 00:59:12.810
I can imagine the same
body growing up in India.

00:59:12.810 --> 00:59:14.730
And it will be a
different Sajit.

00:59:14.730 --> 00:59:16.740
That culture would have
a very different impact

00:59:16.740 --> 00:59:18.335
on him and the
person that he would

00:59:18.335 --> 00:59:21.140
be, would be very different
even though biologically,

00:59:21.140 --> 00:59:24.480
neurobiologically even, it
would be the same material body.

00:59:24.480 --> 00:59:28.750
So the culture--
society is really

00:59:28.750 --> 00:59:32.790
a very, very strong
aspect of who we are.

00:59:32.790 --> 00:59:37.890
But then who we are then
influences the culture.

00:59:37.890 --> 00:59:39.160
So it's a two-way street.

00:59:39.160 --> 00:59:44.690
And in some sense it is
both liberating and binding.

00:59:44.690 --> 00:59:46.750
You can't escape society.

00:59:46.750 --> 00:59:47.850
You can't escape culture.

00:59:47.850 --> 00:59:49.990
It's a large part
of what we are.

00:59:49.990 --> 00:59:51.610
But we can influence it too.

00:59:51.610 --> 00:59:55.530
And so if you see it that
way, then I would say,

00:59:55.530 --> 00:59:56.500
yeah, it's liberating.

00:59:56.500 --> 00:59:58.000
MALE SPEAKER: Very
cool-- very cool.

